Immigration is such a unique experience that if you were an immigrant, people back home won't completely understand you, because you have this "new life". text: Beautiful and so great for the first hour and a half, but when it came time to apply the tension, it just didn't deliver for me. My biggest problem, and it happens all the time in movies and books, is that the protagonist shouldn't have to be reminded of his/her love for the love interest by another character. If I'm to believe that the two are to live happily ever after and that the correct decision was made, the decision should be on the character alone and uninfluenced by anybody else. Her decision ended up feeling like a product of her environment and not just her following her heart. Don't get me wrong, she chose who I felt she should have chosen, but the circumstances around it just killed the authenticity of it. Still one of the best films I've seen this year, disappointment just stings a little worse when it separates great from incredible.   I've really only seen universal acclaim, so feel free to reply and reassure me that I'm not crazy.

text: MY RATING - 6 out of 10. This is the story of a young Irish woman who leaves rural Ireland to live in Brooklyn , New York. Despite her home sickness , she meets a man and falls in love but the lure of going back home threatens to scupper the relationship.  Brooklyn is real old fashioned love story that could quite easily have been made in the 40's or 50's.  Saoirse Ronan is brilliant and is turning into a very accomplished actress . There is also a very good cameo from Julie Walters who plays the very funny Mrs. Kehoe .  Some critics have gushed over this film , I don't quite see that myself but none the less it was quite enjoyable.

text: I really can't understand why this movie didn't "click" with me. 96% on Rotten Tomatoes, that's something! To me, the story had no pulse, it relied a lot on the innocent-looking protagonist, and failed miserably to deliver drama. All I saw is a girl whining about her life while everything is going pretty much ok with it, and then she just SPOILER ALERT easily flirts with the first guy she meets from back home. Sorry I can't root for a wh... cough cough. I just can't. Showing people crying and announcing bad events does not make drama. I was like "why should I give a shit" all the time. One good example of such attempt done right is The Diary. It gets us into all of the main characters' personal little problems too, yet we care. Ellis looks incredibly lovable at first, but that quick and easy transition to being with a second guy and all, just missed me. It started like she came back for her mom, and then she just realises how nice orgasms are and goes after them. To me, the movie has a very foul depiction of women. Unless that's what they want to tell us, that there are no good girls. I would accept that, but I think they tried to make us root for the protagonist, which tottaly failed...

text: I watched this last night and it is beautifully made film in terms of acting, writing and period feel. But most of all, what makes it interesting is the story is of an educated and middle-class Irish girl emigrating to the USA in the 1940s who actually finds her social standing and economic status does not improve upon arriving in Brooklyn.  What I loved most about the story is that it brings home why everyone should move to a foreign country - even if for a while - as it grows you as a human being.  because it is not a Hollywood film there is zero jingoism with no transgender Chinese baker at the end reciting the Gettysburg Address.  It shows what made America great: ordinary decent people.
author: Thomas Sheridan

text: Did anyone watching the movie Brooklyn notice an interesting subplot of the Catholic church removing the most intelligent and prettiest young women from Ireland?  It was a more elegant form of the Magdelene Laundry or Mother and Baby Homes.   The impetus was the same: to rob Ireland of its brightest and most talented so as to boost the power and wealth of the US Catholic Church. The 'kind' priest in the movie was running a highly polish human trafficking operation on behalf of the Vatican. Even when he told her there is nothing in Ireland for her to go back to it was a complete lie. She had an idyllic career, romance and lifestyle in Ireland waiting for her.

text: As an immigrant myself, I find this movie quite superficial... a beautiful happy-ending story. Where are the real difficulties of living abroad in a different culture, where no one understands the little things that belong to you, where foreigners are often seen as a threat...? It seemed to me a little condescending that after a limited period the main character had already forgotten her past to fully embrace her new life. It takes ages ‚Äì if that is ever possible ‚Äì to overcome that feeling of longing, the sense of not belonging somehow... one's soul divided between two countries. No, for me this movie did not touch reality in the slightest.
